"The sea is ours": Inland Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Sailors patrolling the Navy's headquarters, which is shrouded in rain, in La Paz.
On public buildings, there is a sea blue flag.
Fleet bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are painted with the motto: "The sea is ours, it is a right.
It is a duty to take it back".
The memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still strong throughout the inland state of Bolivia, and so is the longing to sail again in the Pacific.
Hopes may be at their highest for decades as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of voting.
"Bolivia has momentum, a sense of community and clarity, and naturally awaits the outcome with a positive outlook", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the International Court of Justice's decision on the big screen throughout the country and hope that the Hague Court will support Bolivia's commitment to negotiate the granting of sovereignty over an area of access to the sea to Chile after decades of negotiations.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic native president, who faces a controversial election campaign next year, is also at stake in the impeachment hearing on Monday.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific", he promised in late August.
But analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will take Bolivia's side and that there would be no major changes if it did.
The United Nations Assembly, which has its seat in the Netherlands, has no power to cede Chilean territory and has stated that it cannot determine the outcome of any possible discussions.
The fact that the International Court of Justice is appealing the verdict only six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case "was not complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of advancing Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have been a setback.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian leadership", said Zárate.
Morales' warlike rhetoric has destroyed the remaining Chilean goodwill, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue the discussions, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end a 139-year era of disagreements and gain mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who remains one of Latin America's most popular presidents, used the maritime problem as a political tool.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific", he added.
"The suspension of the trial is an opportunity to see that we have overcome the past".
