John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have many excellent academic results behind them and continue to do so in 2018 with a number of outstanding results, which are further reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, the arts, music and other local endeavours.
With up to 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can compose and implement a tailored curriculum, we are finding that modern languages remain a popular subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it touches his heart".
It's an important reminder that we can't just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can see from the latest results this year that languages are the top candidate in the statistics for the most independent schools.
In all, 68 percent of students studying foreign languages received the high grade of A.
The data collected by the 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of pupils received A grades in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important competences which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language choice is now being taken at the same level as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons why employers were unable to fill vacancies were due to lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More jobs will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career the young people choose, if they have learned a second language, they will have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competitors.
According to a YouGov opinion poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multilingual percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is important to invest in language education for children today.
When children are able to speak several languages, especially languages from developing countries, they have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages in which they are taught.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK in the run up to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, there is no denying that languages continue to be very important for the future of the country in a global business environment and that this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to the young people of Scotland.
It's got to be done.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
