North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally if there is no confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions reinforce its distrust of the United States and that the country will not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the Worldwide Organization's General Assembly that North Korea had shown "significant goodwill" within the past year, for example by halting nuclear and missile tests, setting up a nuclear testing site and promising not to develop nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not seen a similar reaction from the United States", he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance that we ourselves will take the first step and disarm unilaterally".
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phase-by-phase" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps, his speech seemed important because it did not unambiguously reject unilateral disarmament, as previously had been the case with Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim promised to work on "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has demanded a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to the softening of international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and expands pressure with sanctions to achieve its purpose by force and even opposes 'the declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a wish among people who don't know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are reinforcing our distrust".
Ri did not mention any more plans for a summit between Kim and Trump, as the US leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea rather than the United States, the negotiations would not be so tight".
Nevertheless, the tone of Rice's speech was very different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missile launch on the US mainland was inevitable after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump threatened the UN with "total destruction" of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for his courage in disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea recedes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a timeline for these actions, but said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its steps.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that: "The Security Council must uphold sanctions with conviction and without error until we achieve total, final, confirmed nuclear disarmament".
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously increased economic sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to halt Pyongyang's missile and nuclear weapons program.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines during the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for another meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times during the year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made, while North Korea accused him just hours later of making "cruel demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to close a missile and nuclear facility if the United States took "corresponding steps".
He said Kim had told him that the "compliant steps" he demanded were the security pledges Trump made in Singapore, as well as moves toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students taking a class on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep, and the goal of the course is to counter the growing macho culture where you study all night long and are kept on high levels of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world's best universities often do not know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has completed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the presentation was over, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why do I have to know this now that I'm on the job?'
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits can improve their academic and athletic performance and overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university's health department, says the university decided to offer the course after finding out that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course consists of interactivity.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a college room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how poor sleep affects your athletic performance, and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part of the course, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, blood clots, depression, and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily habits by clicking on various icons on an interactive map of the campus.
"We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect your health", adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride in taking an all-nighter still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
The "secret weapon" against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said. It even counteracts weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain think you're hungry, why you're constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped organize the course last year when he took one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him work on making it a universal course for the entire university.
He hopes that the next step will be for all graduates to be offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up, which can raise awareness of the harmful effects of light from electronic displays that can move at daytime and make falling asleep more difficult.
