Yearbook: The inventor of the geiger counter
And now a page from the yearbook "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today  if we count...  was the day the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger invented a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that would eventually lead to the device known as the geiger counter.
The geiger counter has become a staple of both science and popular culture, as seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans as peasant scientists:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a geiger counter used to find radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms that the radioactivity in the minerals makes".
Evans: "Wait, it's on now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before he would have turned 63.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells as part of treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory
They can then "see" the protein common to many cancers and where they are injected again.
A test vaccine has shown promising results in patients with a number of cancers.
When a woman with ovarian cancer was treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, the cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves removing immune cells from patients and modifying them in the laboratory so that they can "see" the protein called HER2, which many cancers have, and then inject the cells again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine".
HER2 "makes several cancers develop", including breast, ovarian, lung, and intestinal cancers, explains Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach, taking immune cells from patients and "teaching" them to attack cancer cells, has worked in the treatment of a specific type of leukemia.
