Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners Lee joked that the Inrupt plan is "world domination".
"We have to do it now", he said of the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solids technology so people can create their own "online personal data collection" or POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's like if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were available in a single browser at the same time.
What is unique about online personal data collection is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access the specific information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data".
According to Inrupt's CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to bring together resources, processes and capabilities to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, some software developers on project contracts and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee says that he and his team don't talk to "Facebook or Google about whether they should change everything completely so that all of their business models suddenly become redundant".
"We're not asking for your permission".
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to offer commercial energy and an ecosystem that can ensure the integrity and quality of the new Internet built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he started the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
