He also said he was less interested in winning the Olympics after becoming a parent.
The longtime host of the radio show, Kirsty Young, has taken a few months off due to illness.
Daley was a guest on Laverne's first program, and said he felt "less worthwhile" than anyone else in his life because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
He said: "To this day, the feelings of being remembered and feeling different have been the things that have given me the strength to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was "something", he said, so he wouldn't let everyone down when they learned about his sexuality.
The double Olympic bronze medalist has become a high-profile LGBT activist and used her participation in this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for the decriminalization of homosexuality in several countries.
He said that he spoke out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without negative consequences and that he would give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said he was "surprised" when he fell in love with a man  the American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but told me that the age difference had never been a problem.
He said that it's hard to find anyone of his age who has experienced similar ups and downs when you go through so much at such a young age  he went to his first Olympics at age 14, and his father died of cancer three years later.
The couple had a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley in June, and Daley said that "his whole outlook" had changed.
"If you had asked me last year, it would all be about me winning a gold medal", he said.
"But there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie".
His son shares the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley told me that his father didn't accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they had gotten tickets to London 2012 when he was going to sit in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him he wouldn't be there at that time.
I held his hand when his breathing stopped, and it first occurred to me that he was not immortal when he stopped breathing and was dead", he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I just knew that it was what I had dreamed of my whole life - to dive in front of a home crowd at the Olympics.
It was also the inspiration for his first song selection  Proud by Heather Small  which had meant a lot during the Olympics and still gave him goose skin.
