Kick Mickelson on the bench for the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson sets a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup game, but he has to do something about his form if it's not going to be a sad mile.
Mickelson, who is record-setting for the 12th time to compete in the competition, which takes place every two years, was put on the bench by Captain Jim Furyk for Saturday's fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being the center of events for the United States as usual, the five-time winner had to play the game of cheerleading and practice his game in the hope of correcting the pitfalls.
Even at the peak of his career, he was not the most straightforward, which is why the 48-year-old is not a perfect match for the course at Le Golf National, where the long rough often punishes stray shots.
And if the pitch wasn't big enough, Mickelson will be meeting the ever-precise British Open winner Francesco Molinari at game nine on Sunday, who has teamed up with newcomer Tommy Fleetwood to win all four games this week.
If the Americans, who are starting the 12 singles, start strong, Mickelson's fight could be decisive.
Furyk did not show surprising confidence in his teammate.
"He understood his role completely today, slapped me on the back, put his arm around me and said he'd be ready tomorrow", Furyk said.
"He has a great faith in himself".
He's in the Hall of Fame and he's given so much to these teams before  and also this week.
I didn't think he'd play two games.
I imagined he was gonna play more, but that's how it went, and that's how it was.
He wants to be out there like everyone else".
On Sunday, Mickelson broke Nick Faldos record for most games played in the Ryder Cup.
It could be the end of a Ryder Cup career that has never been fully measured by his individual achievements.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, although Furyk said his presence contributes to something indefinable.
"He's funny, he's sarcastic, he's funny, he likes to stick to people, and he's good to have in the team room", he explained.
"I also think the younger players had fun playing against him this week, which was fun to watch.
He contributes much more than just the game".
Captain Thomas Bjørn of Europe knows that great leadership can quickly disappear
European captain Thomas Bjørn knows from experience that a solid lead before the final day of the Ryder Cup singles competition can quickly become nerve-wracking.
The Danish made his debut in 1997 at Valderrama, where a team led by Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but was just about to be recovered before the finish line with a victory of 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"One keeps reminding oneself that we had a good lead in Valderrama, we had a good lead in Brookline, where we lost, and in Valderrama, where we just exactly won", says Bjørn after watching the 2018 team win both 5-3 on Friday and yesterday for an overall lead of 10-6 at Le Golf National.
History tells me and the rest of the team that it's not over.
It's gonna be full of junk by tomorrow.
Go out there and do everything right.
It's not over until you get the points on the board.
We have one goal, and that is to try to win the trophy, and that's where our focus is.
I've always said that I focus on the 12 players on our side, but we also know what's on the other side  the best golfers in the world".
Enchanted by his players' performances on a difficult course, Bjørn added: "I don't take any of this for granted.
Tomorrow is a whole new challenge.
Tomorrow, it is individual achievement that counts, and it is something else entirely.
It's great to be out there with a partner when things are going well, but when you're out there alone, you're tested on all the parameters as a golfer.
That's what players need to understand. Get the best out of yourself tomorrow.
Now you must leave your partner, for he must also bring out the best in himself".
It looks different to opponent Jim Furyk, who hopes for better individual performances than in the partner game with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who won three out of four points.
Fury himself has experienced a lot of hardship on the last day, first on the winning team in Brooklyn before losing when Europe made the Miracle at Medina.
"I remember every word", he said when asked how Captain Ben Crenshaw in 1999 had spoken to his players before the final day.
"We have 12 big games tomorrow, but you want a good start, like you saw at Brooklyn, like you saw at Medina.
Once momentum has found a direction, it puts a lot of pressure on the midfield.
We put our teams together in that order and put the players on the field in the order we feel.
Thomas has been given the task of trying to lead the relegation and will face Rory McIlroy in the top flight, while Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter and the other Europeans play in the first half of the series.
