Germany's new warship is being postponed again
The German navy's latest frigate was supposed to be ready in 2014 to replace Cold War warships, but the Germans have to wait at least another year due to technical problems and an escalating price tag, local media report.
The commissioning of the largest ship in the all-new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, the "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit, citing a spokesman from the military.
The ship was to have joined the fleet in 2014, but compliance problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered back by the fleet in 2007 are to replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a wide range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the new frigates is a lower maintenance requirement: it should be possible to keep the frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships  which are said to make Germany appear as an overseas power factor  will already be outdated when deployed, Die Zeit writes.
The failed F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy delivered a ship back to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media reported a number of critical "software and hardware flaws" that rendered the warship useless in combat situations.
Software errors were of particular importance as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships were to be operated by a crew of 120 sailors  only half the crew of the older Bremen frigates.
It also appeared that the ship was too heavy, which reduced its performance and limited the possibility for the fleet to make future updates.
The 7,000-tonne "Rheinland-Pfalz" is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the cost of the project, which includes training the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an initial price of €2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important given recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government's defence committee, admitted that the fleet was "lack of deployment-ready ships".
The official said that the problem had grown over time because the old ships were taken out of service without being replaced.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were ready to join the fleet.
The National Trust is sneaking into the secret lives of the bats.
New research from an area in the Scottish Highlands tries to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the unique behaviour of flying mammals and will help with future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common bat, dwarf bat, long-horned bat and water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at carefully selected locations in the area to record the activity of bats during the season.
Data from NTS personnel and volunteers are also collected using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the audio recordings will reveal the frequencies of the flying squirrels and show which species do what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour, a report and a map of their habitat are produced.
NTS conservation adviser Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to identify the benefits of habitat conservation efforts such as the establishment of ponds and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the UK has declined dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban development projects that affect shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials, and pet attacks.
The bats are not actually blind.
But because they hunt primarily at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use advanced eco-location techniques to find insects and fly without obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect ships and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve in the area around Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of Scotland's bats.
The area's custodian, David Thompson, says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a really good area for bats", he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
There is much not known about bats, so working here and elsewhere can help them understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on property, as the destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young, putting an entire local population at risk of extinction.
The bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill, disturb or disturb them or their prey.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to join in.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how populations evolve".
