Brexit: Britain 'will forever regret' the loss of carmakers
Britain "will regret it forever" if it lost its status as the world's leading carmaker after Brexit, said Commerce Minister Greg Clark.
He added that it was 'concerning' that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if the UK left the EU without a deal it would temporarily reduce production at the Burnaston plant near Derby.
"We need a deal", Clark said.
The Japanese carmaker said that longer waiting times at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which produces the Toyota Auris and Avensis, produced almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the EU.
"The way I see it, production will stop at our factory if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March", said Burnaston CEO Marvin Cooke.
Other British carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, are expressing fears of leaving the EU without a cross-border trade agreement.
For example, BMW says they will close their Mini factory in Oxford a month after Brexit.
The main concern of car manufacturers is the supply chain risks in the event of a withdrawal without agreement.
Toyota's production runs on a tight schedule, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and the EU.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there could be border problems that the car industry says could lead to delays and a lack of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to store more than one day's production at the Derbyshire plant and then production would be stopped, the company said.
Mr Clark said that Theresa May's Chequers plan for future negotiations with the EU is "composed to precise avoidance of these border checks".
"We need a deal. We want the best deal that not only allows us  as I call it  to enjoy our current success, but to seize this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The statements from Toyota and other manufacturers indicate that we need to be able to continue what has been a successful supply chain".
Toyota could not say how long production would be stopped, but in the long run higher prices would reduce the competitiveness of the factory, which would ultimately cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has been at Burnaston for 24 years and is a trusted colleague at the factory, says that his members are becoming increasingly concerned: "My experience tells me that once these jobs disappear, they will not return".
A government spokesman said: "We have proposed a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU".
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be delayed again, says the White House.
Donald Trump's important meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could "stay postponed for another week" as the list of Supreme Court nominees Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein looks over the shoulder of Special Counsel Robert Mueller as he investigates Russian election meddling, ties between Trump's aides and Russia and the president's possible obstruction of justice.
Whether Trump will fire the Attorney General and thereby jeopardize Mueller's independence has been a topic of talk in Washington for months.
The New York Times reported earlier this month that Rosenstein was considering wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of firing the president via paragraph 25.
Rosenstein denied the news.
But last Monday, he went to the White House, and there was a rumor that he was going to quit.
Instead, a meeting was arranged Thursday with Trump, who was then at the UN headquarters in New York.
Trump said he would "not like" to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was delayed to avoid a collision with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing where Kavanaugh and Christine Blasey Ford, who have accused him of sexual assault, were to testify.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, delaying the Senate election.
Trump's press secretary Sarah Sanders was on Fox News on Sunday.
When asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "There is no date set. It could be this week. I can also imagine that it could be pushed back a week with everything going on in the Supreme Court.
But we have to see, and I like to keep the press updated".
Some journalists would challenge the claim that Sanders has not held a press conference at the White House since September 10.
The host, Chris Wallace, asked her why.
Sanders said the lack of press conferences was not due to TV journalists playing for the gallery, but added: "I don't disagree with the way they play up to the camera".
She then said that the direct contact between Trump and the press would be increased.
"The president is receiving more press questions than any president before him", she said, adding, without citing a source, "We've looked at the numbers".
Press conferences will still be held, Sanders said, but "if the press has the opportunity to ask direct questions to the president of the United States, it is infinitely better than talking to me.
We're trying to give rich opportunities for that, and you've seen us do that over the last few weeks, and that's going to be in the press conference when you can talk to the president of the United States".
Trump often answers questions when he leaves the White House or attends open hearings or press conferences with high-ranking guests.
