Foreign buyers are charged higher voting taxes when they buy houses in the UK
Foreign buyers are charged a higher voting tax when they buy a property in the UK.
This is a feature that will dampen Corbyn's success in attracting young voters.
The higher voting tax will hit those who do not pay taxes in the UK.
The Treasury expects it will provide £120 million a year to the homeless.
Theresa May is today proposing that foreign buyers be charged a higher voting tax when they buy property in the UK for the benefit of the homeless.
The move will be seen as an attempt to counter Jeremy Corbyn's success in attracting young voters with promises of cheaper housing and pursuing those with the highest incomes.
The increase in the polling tax will affect individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK, and the proceeds from this will be used to support the government's campaign to ensure that everyone has a place to sleep.
The additional fee, which is added to the current voting tax and the higher levels introduced two years ago on purchases of multi-family homes and rental purchases, can reach up to 3%.
The Treasury expects it to raise £120 million a year.
It is estimated that 13% of new buildings in London are bought by people living abroad, which causes prices to rise and makes it harder for first time buyers to gain a foothold in the housing market.
Many of the country's rich areas, especially the capital, have become "ghost towns" because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new bill comes just weeks after Boris Johnson proposed a cut in the voting tax to make it easier for young people to buy their first home.
He accused large construction companies of keeping property prices high by buying land they do not use, and he asked May to drop quotas on cheap housing to address Britain's "shameful housing situation".
Corbyn has proposed a series of striking housing reforms, including a check on rental prices and the removal of the landlord's ability to put people on the streets if they comply with the lease.
He will also strengthen the possibility of building public housing.
May said: "Last year I said I would use my presidency to restore the British dream; that life would be better for every generation.
And that means repairing our non-functioning housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
But it cannot be that it is as easy for foreign firms and individuals living outside the UK to buy housing as it is for hardworking Britons.
For too many, the dream of owning a home has become too distant, and the dishonesty of sleeping on the street is still too common".
