Indonesia is seismically on the so-called Pacific Rim and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Some of the most devastating earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years have been:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26, which struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the coastline of the Indian Ocean, including more than half of those in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, and triggered a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of the Western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh, spreading destruction and panic as the population was reminded of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
